AGENTIC-VT 1.0

[metadata]
title: MIRA's New Smart Glasses Could Give you AIG Level 2nd Brain - The Small Glasses Giants are PISSED!
channel: @octopusinc_
source: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lFlzZuIyy-I
upload_date: 20260515
transcript_source: captions
route: text

---

[00:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'There\'s a specific kind of embarrassment that hits when you\'re in a meeting and someone asks you about a detail from a conversation you had two weeks ago. You know it was important, but it\'s just gone. That blank moment where your brain'

[00:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'just comes up empty. What if that never had to happen again? Not because you started taking better notes, not because you downloaded yet another productivity app, but because a pair of glasses'

[00:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'sitting on your face was quietly listening to your entire day, remembering everything for you, and whispering the answer directly onto your lens before you even have time to feel embarrassed. That is the actual real'

[00:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'pitch behind Mira glasses. And the more I dug into this thing, the more I genuinely could not stop thinking about it. Mira was founded by two Harvard'

[00:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'dropouts named Anfu Nguyen and Kean Ardaiz Feo. Now, these aren\'t some tech bros with a pitch deck. These guys built flamethrowers and robotic tentacles in Harvard\'s maker space before they even'

[01:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'started working on smart glasses. They went viral with an early prototype that racked up over 80 million views online. 80 million. That\'s not a niche audience, that\'s a cultural moment. They dropped'

[01:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'out, raised $6.6 million seed round led by General Catalyst, and got to work on turning the viral demo into an actual product. The company was originally called Halo, but they rebranded it to'

[01:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Mira, which I think was a smart move. General Catalyst, by the way, is not a small name in venture capital. These are the people who backed Airbnb, Stripe, and Snap in early stages. When they lead a seed round for a hardware startup, the'

[01:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'core mission is blunt, and I respect it. Anfu and Kean believe human memory is a fundamental cognitive bottleneck, not a minor inconvenience, a bottleneck. And they built Mira specifically to solve'

[01:56] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'it. Now, let me walk you through the actual hardware before we get into capabilities because the specs matter here. The glasses is weigh 39 g. That\'s lighter than most regular frames you\'d'

[02:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'pick up at an optician. They run for over 10 hours on a single charge, and they\'re fully rechargeable in 40 minutes. The display is dual wave guide system running at 60 Hz designed to be readable both indoors and outdoors. Mira'

[02:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'is also fully prescription compatible using 1.74 high index lenses to keep the frames thin and light, and critically, there\'s no camera. That last point is deliberate, and I honestly think it\'s'

[02:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'one of the smartest decision they could have made. No camera means no recording faces, no privacy panic, no one at the restaurant staring at you wondering if you\'re filming them. Just audio. Now,'

[02:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'here\'s where it gets genuinely impressive. Mira glasses have a microphone that is always on. They continuously transcribe everything you say and everything that is said around you. That transcription gets sent to'

[03:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'your phone, stored locally on your device, and not on Mira\'s servers. The raw audio is permanently deleted the instant it has been transcribed. They don\'t sell you data, they don\'t train'

[03:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'models on it. It\'s just your transcript saved for you. The AI layer on top of that transcription is where the super brain label starts to make actual sense. The system achieves sub 700 ms response'

[03:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'times. To give you a reference point, the average human blink takes about 150 to 400 ms. So, by the time you blink twice, Mira has already pulled context'

[03:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'from your conversation history, process the question, and display the answer on your lens. That speed matters because anything slower than that doesn\'t feel like thought. It feels like using a device. At sub 700 ms, it starts to feel'

[03:49] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'like actual memory. Now, real-time translation is probably the feature I keep coming back to. Humane supports over 60 languages, and the translation happens live through your lenses as'

[04:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'someone is speaking. If you\'ve ever sat in a meeting with someone whose first language isn\'t yours, or maybe tried to navigate a foreign country with a phone pressed to your face, you already'

[04:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'understand why this is significant. A user review I came across described trying the live translation with a Mandarin-speaking family member visiting from Taiwan and said it genuinely eased the language gap. That\'s not a use case,'

[04:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'that\'s a real human moment. Then, there\'s the memory feature, which is the core of the whole product. Every conversation you\'ve had while wearing these glasses is indexed and searchable. You can query your own post. Someone'

[04:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'mentions a project name from a meeting 3 weeks ago, and you can pull the full context from the conversation instantly right onto your lens. No notes, no phone, no interrupting the flow of the'

[04:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'current conversation to go digging. The proactive AI layer is the part that I think divides people most. Humane doesn\'t just wait for you to ask it something. It listens to what\'s happening around you and surfaces'

[05:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'relevant information before you even think to ask. If you\'re discussing a topic and there\'s relevant context from a past conversation, it will surface that. If you\'re about to walk into a meeting and it knows you\'ve discussed'

[05:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'certain topics with those people before, it can prepare you. On top of that, the agentic features are expanding. The app already supports scheduling calendar events, sending emails, and making phone calls directly from the glasses. You can'

[05:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'create up to three custom skills, essentially custom AI behaviors tailored to your own specific work. That level of personalization is rare in wearable tech. Pricing sits at $649'

[05:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'for the glasses. Core features, including unlimited transcription, note-taking, and translation, are all free. The optional AI assistant tier for unlimited queries costs $20 per month.'

[05:58] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Now, I need to be honest, and I\'m not going to pretend that the always-on microphone isn\'t worth talking about seriously. It absolutely is. A device that listens to every conversation you'

[06:10] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'have all day long is a significant thing to put on your face. And I think it\'s fair to sit with that for a minute. The architecture Mira chose is genuinely as privacy-respecting as always-on audio can be right now.'

[06:23] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Audio is deleted instantly, transcripts live on your phone, and nothing trains on your data. They deliberately excluded a camera to reduce the surveillance footprint, and the founders have been'

[06:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'vocal about this not being incidental, but a core design philosophy. That said, the people around haven\'t consented to being transcribed are a real consideration. Mira\'s position in that'

[06:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'transcription is functionally equivalent to note-taking, similar to how you might take notes in a meeting. That\'s a reasonable framing, but it\'s a conversation that society is still working through with wearable tech'

[07:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'broadly. My honest read on this is that the privacy architecture is genuinely thoughtful for a consumer product, and the no-camera choice was the right call. I think the concerns are a real and worth taking seriously, but they\'re not'

[07:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'deal-breakers for the value that this technology actually delivers. Now, the obvious comparison is Ray-Ban Meta glasses. Those are stylish, comfortable, and have solid AI features, but here\'s'

[07:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the key difference Mira keeps pointing to, and I think it\'s accurate. Meta\'s glasses help you when you ask them something. Mira helps you all the time. Meta\'s glasses don\'t have persistent memory of your conversation. Mira does.'

[07:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Meta\'s glasses don\'t know your history, your preferences, who you talk to regularly, what projects you\'re working on. Mira builds the context over time. One early user who owned both Meta'

[07:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Ray-Bans and Halide glasses said Mira showed more utility in 10 minutes than both of those pairs combined. That is a strong statement from someone with real comparison evidence.'

[08:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Now, I\'ll be straight with you. I find Mira genuinely exciting in a way I haven\'t felt about a piece of consumer tech in a while, especially wearables. Not because it\'s a gimmick or because'

[08:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the marketing is good, but because the core thesis is correct. Memory is a bottleneck. Most of what limits us cognitively in a professional and personal context isn\'t intelligence. It\'s recall. It\'s context. It\'s having'

[08:31] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the right information at the right moment. Mira is betting that the right form factor for solving that isn\'t a phone, isn\'t a near bot, and isn\'t a chatbot. It\'s a pair of glasses that knows your life. I think that bet is a'

[08:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'reasonable one. The hardware is surprisingly solid for a first-generation product. The latency is genuinely impressive. The no camera call shows real self-awareness about what the market will actually accept. Will it be'

[08:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'perfect out the gate? No. The Android app doesn\'t exist yet. Some features are still early, and the app being open in the background was a legitimate complaint that the team had to address'

[09:09] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'publicly. These are real growing pains, but the foundation here is serious. Real investors, real founders, real hardware, and a problem that genuinely matters to most people. The cognitive co-pilot'

[09:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'category is forming right now, and Mira is one of the most interesting early bets in it. If you\'re the kind of person who lives in meetings, works across languages, or just constantly feels like your brain is at capacity, I think MIRA'

[09:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'is worth paying very close attention to. This isn\'t a gadget for gadget people. It isn\'t a gimmick. This is a tool for people who want to think better. And'

[09:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'honestly, I\'m here for it.'
